                "author_name": "A Google User", 
                "language": "en", 
                "rating": 5, 
                "text": "I remember the first time stepping into OCBC as a kid, I was in total awe at the level of refinement in the facility. Now, 9 years later, I can say I experienced much the same feeling my first time at LABC. Now the facility is actually unfinished, although I doubt anyone would really notice or even be able to tell since all the things that you need for playing badminton are there(courts, lights, pro shop). However, apparently there are going to be restaurants and yoga classes or something but I won't be able to cover that obviously. \n\nAs for everything that's up and running, which is everything you'd really need, it's all just fantastic. The bathrooms are incredibly clean; if a bald person played badminton with a head this clean, he would be able to blind his opponents with intense glare. The flooring is soft and bouncy to prevent any injury, but firm enough still to let you play as fast as you want. Think of it as achieving that perfect balance like really great fashion: something that looks great and catches your eye, but not so much that it screams out and makes you look desperate. There are 15 courts, which you can appreciate whether you are as impatient as someone who's late for a date or as tolerant as a teacher for mentally challenged children. The courts are all Yonex mats too, so players of the highest caliber can enjoy this facility, but even beginners can enjoy having proper courts to play on.\n\nThe air conditioning should be enough to lull you to this club over the other local clubs though, since this is the only one in the area that has it. With all the gas guzzling SUVs people drive, we are feeling the full effects of global warming this summer, so it's a blessing to have this facility pop up just this year. The timing almost makes it seem like there are some divine powers at play here.\n\nLastly, the price. Well, it's more expensive than other clubs nearby, but really, it ought to be. I recently overheard someone saying that he was surprised the price increased because there's so much competition. I don't like to argue with strangers so I didn't say anything naturally, but I thought to myself, those other clubs are hardly competition at all. I don't mean to put down the other clubs in the region, but I would say that we're comparing facilities that are really too different. I mean it's equivalent to comparing a Jag to a Kia. Sure, they're both cars, but the only real reason you'd get a Kia over a Jag is if you can't afford it, or worse, are really cheap. \n\nSeriously though, I see people buying nice shoes and rackets, but saying the price is too high, which I really can't understand. Health is really the last thing you should be saving on, and for the sake of your precious knees which you pressure so much during play, you really should play here if financially possible.",

                "language": "en", 
                "rating": 5, 
                "text": "I'm almost reluctant to review Crockett Park because it's one of the best kept secrets I know! I came here when I was a Girl Scout many years ago and my troop drove here around 8/9pm to do some stargazing. The Northern Virginia Astronomy Club (NOVAC) was also there that night doing one of their public events and some of the members brought telescopes. They pointed out various celestial objects, constellations, and stars in the night sky to us - a very interactive and fun learning experience. Crockett Park has a large open field that offers unobstructed views of the night sky. \n\nIf you want to be able to see numerous stars and constellations, maybe even a planet or two, you have to drive out quite a ways from the light pollution of the city. Midland is about a 50 minute drive from the outer suburbs (like Fairfax) of D.C. The view is absolutely breathtaking. Prior to my visit here, I had never seen so many stars, constellations, nebula, meteors, or planets in the night sky. The sky was pitch black and glittered with millions and millions of twinkling lights. I could even see the Milky Way and it was such a spectacular sight looking at the glowing band arching across the sky. To think that there's a place near D.C. where you can actually see the galaxy of our solar system is just so amazing. \n\nNOVAC does monthly public viewings at Crockett Park (as well as Sky Meadows State Park in Delaplane), so you can get a chance to stargaze and learn from experienced amateur astronomers about the night sky. These viewings happen on Saturday nights until 11pm, so you're able to get into the park after dusk. You can bring your own binoculars or telescopes but it's not needed. It cannot be stressed enough how gorgeous the view is. I highly recommend anyone with an interest in stargazing to come out to Crockett Park on a clear night and look up into the cosmos. An incredible, (literally) out of this world experience!",

THE OTHER REVIEW IS A FAKE!\n\nI used to give this gym a favorable rating, but with how incredibly poorly I was treated, I've downgraded this place to the lowest star rating and am going to another gym. Here's an updated version of my original review:\n\nPOSITIVES\n\n-- Very clean gym.\n\n-- New cardio and weightlifting equipment (from 2008-2010).\n\n-- Not overcrowded\n\n-- Decent location (right in the Wheeling Park District)\n\n-- Cost is reasonable if you sign up for a year plan, either as a full payment or monthly payments. (Residents are only charged $31/month for the base price.)\n\n-- Good building facility with lots of parking.\n\n-- WiFi access\n\n-- Excellent front desk help. (Very nice people)\n\n-- Rave reviews about some of the trainers.\n\n-- Not the stuffiness and impersonal nature you get with franchise gyms.\n\nNEGATIVES\n\n-- Hours are VERY limited. Only open until 5 pm on Sunday, and 6 pm on Saturday!\n\n-- No jacuzzi or sauna\n\n-- No group fitness classes included. (Those are all extra cost. However this can make sense if you don't want to pay extra for that. And they do offer single punch card payments as well as a for everything. So that can be a plus.)\n\n-- You have to walk out of the gym and through a building hallway to get to the regular locker rooms. (Their \"private\" locker rooms are an extra cost.)\n\n-- Top management is extremely poor on guest feedback and customer service. I was encourage to submit my suggestions, which I did via both the suggestion box and emails over the 15 months I was there. All I ever received for my suggestions and questions about using social media and online video was a form response from the Park Director, Matt Wehby. (The standard \"we'll take that into consideration,\" which is really a complete blow-off. When I asked again if I could have a reason why they weren't getting involved more with social media, he refused to give any answer.) An important lesson: Don't ask your members for feedback if you aren't actually willing to be genuinely responsive.\n\n-- Very restrictive on doing any social media. Park District Director Matt Wehby is an extremely rude individual when you ask him about this topic. He was actually clueless that the Park District has it's own Facebook page (albeit just for trivia). He won't allow staff to connect with members via social media, or do how-to videos, or testimonials -- even though commercial competitors are doing it.\n\nFINAL REVIEW\n\nIt's way too expensive for all limitations compared with what other options are available, and the top management is not responsive to customers. Even by the standards of a being part of a community center, they're really not as much into the \"community\" portion as they should be. I can only recommend this for the person who lives really close by and doesn't want to go a couple extra miles to another gym, doesn't care to work out at home, and only wants a small clean gym with no interest in group classes.                 "text": "I came here after work for a Happy Hour with some co-workers. I was excited because I'm a Montrosian and figured that this bar would encapsulate some of the neighborhood's vibe.  I think that it was a pretty nice place to spend some time after work but I wouldn't go out of my way to visit again.  First off, the valet service is quite imposing.  I ride a motorcycle and parked it on the edge of valet and they made me move it twice so they had more space (the lot was never filled).  I feel like in one of the most socially conscious parts of the city riding a motorbike shouldn't be an issue.  As for the restaurant, it was passable, the outdoor area is expansive with various activities and seating.  The food seemed to be a pretty standard, pump it out and fill the people up.  Probably similar to an Applebee's or Chili's. The lighting, as others have noted, was quite poor once the sun went down but I didn't stay much after 7 so not a huge issue.  As for the bar, I ordered a Rye Manhattan and the tender seemed happy to make it, the only issue was when he brought it to me in a martini glass with a maraschino cherry in it.  Not a huge deal, but in Texas where anything remotely 'not manly' is judged, I got a few laughs from co-workers.  It tasted alright, they forgot the bitters but it was passable nothing special or 'craft' about it.  The next one I specifically noted the correct glassware to use and they were cool with it. They did play good music though, it really didn't reflect the vibe of the venue (they are trying to mix Midtown, Montrose, and possibly Katy) and the staff was very accommodating and friendly but definitely not experienced behind the bar. Owner-train your people. \n\nOverall, it was a decent place. Not bad for a Saturday afternoon in nice weather I suppose.  But if you want good drinks, I'd go somewhere else.
